main event: A cigar-shaped object, estimated to be about 200 feet long and 30 feet in diameter, was observed near Saipan Island in the Mariana Islands on April 6, 1950.
interesting points: The object was described as having distinctive markings or features on its surface that appeared to be windows or portholes.
The object was observed by the flight crew of a U.S. Navy attack aircraft and was seen for approximately 2 minutes before disappearing.
The object was reported to be traveling at high speed and in level flight, with no engine noise or other propulsion observed.
Another sighting near Saipan Island occurred about 2 months ago, where a circular-shaped object about the size of a small automobile was seen, with flashing red, green, and white lights.

A separate report describes an elongated cylindrical-shaped object, approximately 150 feet in length, that was observed maneuvering low over the water at high speed (over 600 knots) near Saipan Island on April 7, 1960.
sighted object: cigar-shaped object, circular-shaped object, elongated cylindrical-shaped object
location: Vicinity of Saipan Island, Mariana Islands
witnesses: Flight crew of U.S. Navy attack aircraft, multiple unidentified witnesses
photographs: yes, the report includes photographs of unidentified objects
